OK.

00:38:55.390 --> 00:39:01.980
Well, now what I want to do
is just put up a slightly

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:05.470
different kind of diagram, but
different in an important way.

00:39:05.470 --> 00:39:09.830
Namely, instead of showing the
mole fractions as a function

00:39:09.830 --> 00:39:11.640
of the pressure.

00:39:11.640 --> 00:39:14.680
And I haven't written it in,
but all of these are at

00:39:14.680 --> 00:39:16.030
constant temperature, right?

00:39:16.030 --> 00:39:17.820
I've assumed the temperature
is constant

00:39:17.820 --> 00:39:19.480
in all these things.

00:39:19.480 --> 00:39:22.410
Now let's consider the other
possibility, the other simple

00:39:22.410 --> 00:39:25.960
possibility, which is, let's
hold the pressure constant and

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:26.960
vary the temperature.

00:39:26.960 --> 00:39:29.270
Of course, you know in the lab,
that's usually what's

00:39:29.270 --> 00:39:31.920
easiest to do.

00:39:31.920 --> 00:39:35.350
Now, unfortunately, the
arithmetic gets more

00:39:35.350 --> 00:39:36.600
complicated.

00:39:36.600 --> 00:39:41.070
It's not monumentally
complicated, but here in this

00:39:41.070 --> 00:39:45.820
case, where you have one linear
relationship, which is

00:39:45.820 --> 00:39:46.630
very convenient.

00:39:46.630 --> 00:39:48.080
From Raoult's law.

00:39:48.080 --> 00:39:52.740
And then you have one non-linear
relationship there

00:39:52.740 --> 00:39:54.970
for the mole fraction
of the gas.

00:39:54.970 --> 00:39:59.180
In the case of temperature,
they're both,

00:39:59.180 --> 00:40:01.960
neither one is linear.

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:03.730
Nevertheless, we can just
sketch what the

00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:04.850
diagram looks like.

00:40:04.850 --> 00:40:07.160
And of course it's very useful
to do that, and see how to

00:40:07.160 --> 00:40:10.370
read off it.

00:40:10.370 --> 00:40:13.370
And I should say the derivation
of the curves isn't

00:40:13.370 --> 00:40:14.530
particularly complicated.

00:40:14.530 --> 00:40:16.850
It's not particularly more
complicated than what I think

00:40:16.850 --> 00:40:19.600
you saw last time
to derive this.

00:40:19.600 --> 00:40:21.600
There's no complicated
math involved.

00:40:21.600 --> 00:40:24.730
But the point is, the derivation
doesn't yield a

00:40:24.730 --> 00:40:28.900
linear relationship for either
the gas or the liquid part of

00:40:28.900 --> 00:40:54.730
the coexistence curve.

00:40:54.730 --> 00:41:03.140
OK, so we're going to look at
temperature and mole fraction

00:41:03.140 --> 00:41:04.270
phase diagrams.

00:41:04.270 --> 00:41:06.460
Again, a little more complicated
mathematically but

00:41:06.460 --> 00:41:20.160
more practical in real use.

00:41:20.160 --> 00:41:31.570
And this is T. And here is the,
sort of, form that these

00:41:31.570 --> 00:41:33.130
things take.

00:41:33.130 --> 00:41:35.680
So again, neither
one is linear.

00:41:35.680 --> 00:41:38.430
Up here, now, of course if you
raise the temperatures, that's

00:41:38.430 --> 00:41:41.120
where you end up with gas.

00:41:41.120 --> 00:41:42.310
If you lower the temperature,
you

00:41:42.310 --> 00:41:48.790
condense and get the liquid.

00:41:48.790 --> 00:41:55.620
So, this is TA star.

00:41:55.620 --> 00:42:00.970
TB star.

00:42:00.970 --> 00:42:05.020
So now I want to stick
with A as the

00:42:05.020 --> 00:42:07.590
more volatile component.

00:42:07.590 --> 00:42:11.030
At constant temperature, that
meant that pA star is bigger

00:42:11.030 --> 00:42:12.200
than pB star.

00:42:12.200 --> 00:42:16.480
In other words, the vapor
pressure over pure liquid A is

00:42:16.480 --> 00:42:23.150
higher than the vapor pressure
over pure liquid B. Similarly,

00:42:23.150 --> 00:42:25.380
now I've got constant pressure
and really what I'm looking

00:42:25.380 --> 00:42:26.990
at, let's say I'm at the
limit where I've

00:42:26.990 --> 00:42:30.310
got the pure liquid.

00:42:30.310 --> 00:42:33.910
Or the pure A. And now I'm going
to, let's say, raise the

00:42:33.910 --> 00:42:38.920
temperature until I'm at the
liquid-gas equilibrium.

00:42:38.920 --> 00:42:42.500
That's just the boiling point.

00:42:42.500 --> 00:42:45.820
So if A is the more volatile
component, it has the lower

00:42:45.820 --> 00:42:47.800
boiling point.

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:49.370
And that's what this reflects.

00:42:49.370 --> 00:42:54.280
So higher pB star A corresponds
to lower TA star

00:42:54.280 --> 00:42:59.230
A. Which is just the boiling
point of pure A.

00:42:59.230 --> 00:43:11.690
So, this is called
the bubble line.

00:43:11.690 --> 00:43:14.990
That's called the dew line.

00:43:14.990 --> 00:43:17.630
All that means is, let's say
I'm at high temperature.

00:43:17.630 --> 00:43:19.370
I've got all gas.

00:43:19.370 --> 00:43:21.090
Right no coexistence,
no liquid yet.

00:43:21.090 --> 00:43:23.130
And I start to cool
things off.

00:43:23.130 --> 00:43:25.820
Just to where I just barely
start to get liquid.

00:43:25.820 --> 00:43:29.230
What you see that as is,
dew starts forming.

00:43:29.230 --> 00:43:30.570
A little bit of condensation.

00:43:30.570 --> 00:43:32.765
If you're outside, it means on
the grass a little bit of dew

00:43:32.765 --> 00:43:34.440
is forming.

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:38.300
Similarly, if I start at low
temperature, all liquid now I

00:43:38.300 --> 00:43:41.660
start raising the temperature
until I just start to boil.

00:43:41.660 --> 00:43:46.180
I just start to see the
first bubbles forming.

00:43:46.180 --> 00:43:51.650
And so that's why these things
have those names.

00:43:51.650 --> 00:43:56.090
So now let's just follow along
what happens when I do the

00:43:56.090 --> 00:43:57.780
same sort of thing that
I illustrated there.

00:43:57.780 --> 00:44:00.730
I want to start at one point
in this phase diagram.

00:44:00.730 --> 00:44:04.890
And then start changing
the conditions.

00:44:04.890 --> 00:44:17.610
So let's start here.

00:44:17.610 --> 00:44:19.330
So I'm going to start all
in the liquid phase.

00:44:19.330 --> 00:44:22.200
That is, the temperature
is low.

00:44:22.200 --> 00:44:23.970
Here's xB.

00:44:26.670 --> 00:44:27.690
And my original temperature.

00:44:27.690 --> 00:44:34.570
Now I'm going to raise it.

00:44:34.570 --> 00:44:39.590
So if I raise it a little bit,
I reach a point at which I

00:44:39.590 --> 00:44:41.600
first start to boil.

00:44:41.600 --> 00:44:47.890
Start to find some gas
above the liquid.

00:44:47.890 --> 00:44:51.880
And if I look right here,
that'll be my composition.

00:44:51.880 --> 00:44:53.430
Let me raise it a little
farther, now that we've

00:44:53.430 --> 00:44:57.100
already seen the lever
rule and so forth.

00:44:57.100 --> 00:44:58.140
I'll raise it up to here.

00:44:58.140 --> 00:45:11.790
And that means that out here,
I suppose I should do here.

00:45:11.790 --> 00:45:18.730
So, here is the liquid mole
fraction at temperature two.

00:45:18.730 --> 00:45:23.320
xB at temperature two.

00:45:23.320 --> 00:45:27.640
This is yB at temperature two.

00:45:27.640 --> 00:45:33.860
The gas mole fraction.

00:45:33.860 --> 00:45:37.840
So as you should expect, what's
going to happen here is

00:45:37.840 --> 00:45:43.510
that the gas, this is going to
be lower in B. A, that means

00:45:43.510 --> 00:45:45.570
that the mole fraction
of A must be

00:45:45.570 --> 00:45:47.020
higher in the gas phase.

00:45:47.020 --> 00:45:49.700
That's one minus yB.

00:45:49.700 --> 00:46:05.340
So xA is one minus -- yA, which
is one minus yB higher

00:46:05.340 --> 00:46:10.970
in gas phase.

00:46:10.970 --> 00:46:16.370
Than xA, which is
one minus xB.

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:20.480
In other words, the less
volatile component is enriched

00:46:20.480 --> 00:46:39.100
up in the gas phase.

00:46:39.100 --> 00:46:42.320
Now, what does that mean?

00:46:42.320 --> 00:46:46.890
That means I could follow the
same sort of procedure that I

00:46:46.890 --> 00:46:50.710
indicated before when we looked
at the pressure mole

00:46:50.710 --> 00:46:51.930
fraction phase diagram.

00:46:51.930 --> 00:46:54.970
Namely, I could do this
and now I could

00:46:54.970 --> 00:46:57.150
take the gas phase.

00:46:57.150 --> 00:47:01.730
Which has less of B. It
has more of A. And

00:47:01.730 --> 00:47:03.780
I can collect it.

00:47:03.780 --> 00:47:05.210
And then I can reduce
the temperature.

00:47:05.210 --> 00:47:06.310
So it liquefies.

00:47:06.310 --> 00:47:08.820
So I can condense it,
in other words.

00:47:08.820 --> 00:47:11.820
So now I'm going to start with,
let's say I lower the

00:47:11.820 --> 00:47:14.710
temperature enough so I've got
basically pure liquid.

00:47:14.710 --> 00:47:17.500
But its composition is the
same as the gas here.

00:47:17.500 --> 00:47:19.850
Because of course that's what
that liquid is formed from.

00:47:19.850 --> 00:47:23.800
I collected the gas
and separated it.

00:47:23.800 --> 00:47:25.830
So now I could start
all over again.

00:47:25.830 --> 00:47:31.240
Except instead of being here,
I'll be down here.

00:47:31.240 --> 00:47:33.060
And then I can raise the
temperature again.

00:47:33.060 --> 00:47:35.020
To some place where I choose.

00:47:35.020 --> 00:47:37.350
I could choose here, and
go all the way to hear.

00:47:37.350 --> 00:47:39.120
A great amount of enrichment.

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:41.305
But I know from the lever rule
that if I do that, I'm going

00:47:41.305 --> 00:47:44.460
to have precious little
material over here.

00:47:44.460 --> 00:47:46.730
So I might prefer to raise the
temperature a little more.

00:47:46.730 --> 00:47:50.940
Still get a substantial
amount of enrichment.

00:47:50.940 --> 00:47:54.370
And now I've got, in the gas
phase, I'll further enriched

00:47:54.370 --> 00:47:57.880
in component A. And again
I can collect the gas.

00:47:57.880 --> 00:48:00.850
Condense it.

00:48:00.850 --> 00:48:03.280
Now I'm out here somewhere, I've
got all liquid and I'll

00:48:03.280 --> 00:48:04.350
raise the temperature again.

00:48:04.350 --> 00:48:07.380
And I can again keep walking
my way over.

00:48:07.380 --> 00:48:11.640
And that's what happens during
an ordinary distillation.

00:48:11.640 --> 00:48:17.270
Each step of the distillation
walks along in the phase

00:48:17.270 --> 00:48:23.530
diagram at some selected
point.

00:48:23.530 --> 00:48:25.190
And of course what you're
doing is, you're always

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:27.520
condensing the gas.

00:48:27.520 --> 00:48:30.830
And starting with fresh liquid
that now is enriched in more

00:48:30.830 --> 00:48:33.860
volatile of the components.

00:48:33.860 --> 00:48:36.680
So of course if you're really
purifying, say, ethanol from

00:48:36.680 --> 00:48:39.710
an ethanol water mixture,
that's how you do it.

00:48:39.710 --> 00:48:41.640
Ethanol is the more volatile
component.

00:48:41.640 --> 00:48:42.870
So a still is set up.

00:48:42.870 --> 00:48:45.080
It will boil the stuff and
collect the gas and and

00:48:45.080 --> 00:48:45.920
condense it.

00:48:45.920 --> 00:48:48.350
And boil it again,
and so forth.

00:48:48.350 --> 00:48:50.600
And the whole thing can be set
up in a very efficient way.

00:48:50.600 --> 00:48:53.420
So you have essentially
continuous distillation.

00:48:53.420 --> 00:48:56.970
Where you have a whole sequence
of collection and

00:48:56.970 --> 00:49:00.610
condensation and reheating
and so forth events.

00:49:00.610 --> 00:49:03.930
So then, in a practical way,
it's possible to walk quite

00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:10.870
far along the distillation,
the coexistence curve, and

00:49:10.870 --> 00:49:16.630
distill to really a high
degree of purification.

00:49:16.630 --> 00:49:22.270
Any questions about
how that works?

